body:
Summarising this is a little tricky, but I have produced a cut-down code example that replicates the behaviour I'm seeing which is from a build of latest master (`verilator --version` reports `Verilator 5.009 devel rev v5.008-91-g0b96789e6`) running under Ubuntu 20 LTS (GCC version `gcc (Ubuntu 11.3.0-1ubuntu1~22.04) 11.3.0`).

The RTL below has a variable `ready`. In the trace from the simulation `ready` goes high and stays high which is not the expected behaviour. The values from the trace are not consistent with the values reported by the `always@(posedge clk)` block that has a display statement giving the value of `ready`.

```systemverilog
typedef struct packed {
  logic [31:0] addr;
  logic [31:0] wdata;
  logic        write;
} mem_req_t;

module verilator_bug ();
  logic clk;

  initial begin
    $dumpfile("trace.fst");
    $dumpvars;

    clk = 0;

    forever begin
      #5 clk = ~clk;
    end
  end

  initial begin
    #1000;
    $finish();
  end

  logic        ready;
  logic [31:0] addr;
  logic        write;
  logic [31:0] wdata;

  always @(posedge clk) begin
    $display("Ready is %d at time %t", ready, $time());
  end

  assign addr  = '0;
  assign write = 1'b0;
  assign wdata = '0;

  initial begin
    int ready_delay;
    mem_req_t new_req;

    forever begin
      ready = 1'b0;

      ready_delay = 10;
      for (int i = 0;i < ready_delay; ++i) begin
        @(posedge clk);
      end

      ready = 1'b1;

      new_req = '{
        addr:  addr,
        wdata: wdata,
        write: write
      };

      @(posedge clk);
      #1;
    end
  end
endmodule
```

With the above code in a file `verilog_bug.sv` the following reproduces the issue:

```
verilator --binary --trace-fst verilator_bug.sv
./obj_dir/Vverilator_bug
```

The stdout shows `ready` (as observed by the display statement) toggling between 0 and 1 at various points as expected. The trace in `trace.fst` shows `ready` go high once and it stays high.

I have tried to cut this down further but any more reduction in the RTL seems to restore correct behaviour.
